<div id="review_1994746287" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1994746287" />
    <a title="Orient" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/43587353-orient"><img alt="Orient" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1500791761p2/43587353.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1994746287?book_show_action=true">Jul 15, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Orient" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Orient" href="/user/show/43587353-orient">Orient</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9780345512659" href="/book/show/7177256-the-warded-man">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/43587353-orient?shelf=bloody-romance">bloody-romance</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/43587353-orient?shelf=psychological">psychological</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/43587353-orient?shelf=desperado">desperado</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/43587353-orient?shelf=2017">2017</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/43587353-orient?shelf=hero">hero</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/43587353-orient?shelf=killer">killer</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/43587353-orient?shelf=recs-by-gavin">recs-by-gavin</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1994746287" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4084971630194590186"><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1500130797i/23302380.jpg' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/>This book turned my attention after reading a great review of <b>Gavin</b> :) I’ll try and put my incoherent rambling to match at least 1% of his great review. <br/><br/>My journey started when the author led me into the world of monsters that rise in the night and attack humans who hide behind wards, fascinating old times with herb-gatherers, jongleurs and messengers, who are the only ones who dare to travel far despite danger to bring messages and goods for exchange. Interesting for sure! And the symbols in th</span>
  <span id="freeText4084971630194590186" style="display:none"><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1500130797i/23302380.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>This book turned my attention after reading a great review of <b>Gavin</b> :) I’ll try and put my incoherent rambling to match at least 1% of his great review. <br><br>My journey started when the author led me into the world of monsters that rise in the night and attack humans who hide behind wards, fascinating old times with herb-gatherers, jongleurs and messengers, who are the only ones who dare to travel far despite danger to bring messages and goods for exchange. Interesting for sure! And the symbols in the beginning of the chapters, I loved them, so interesting and unique :)<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1500130797i/23302381._SY540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>However, for some reasons, I’ll mention soon, the book is a strange blend of fun interesting world and some fuzzy stuff.<br><br>The ordinary life of ordinary people was described in a great, interesting way, I could imagine the small villages, the bigger towns, with their own traditions, culture, guilds, governing system and people. That’s cool as I’m more a character driven reader and worldbuilding goes on the second place to me when I read a book, worldbuilding rarely gets praises from me. Though, I must confess, I had some issues with it in this book. I mean religion. It vaguely reminded me of <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Christianity <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>, but it wasn’t clear, more in the shadows and that’s not very good as the legends in the book are based on it. I hope I’ll get more information on that in further books. Also I needed more info on wards and monsters, maybe an additional glance into the world of monsters (<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[I mean the scene when Arlen was sucked into Core and dang it, he escaped even without knocking on the door! <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>), some going back a century to see how the wards were created (there was a small sneak peek, but I was a bit disappointed that the further explanations ended with it). <br><br>Now, my most awaited part. Characters. This book is a journey of three protagonists, who discover their roles in life, though being different personalities with different POVs, but they all understand: to live, means to fight. <br><br>The main character and the main reason for this book is a difficult person. I liked the way he traveled to reach his goal, not always accepting his decisions (<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[I mean leaving the beloved ones, eating demon’s flesh <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>), but the outcome, wow. He’s a character I can def root for. His transformation was expected and I was so eager to dive into it with him, but for some reason the author skipped this. Dang it! <br><br><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1500130797i/23302382._SY540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Arlen and his horsey <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br><br>I enjoyed his sidekick a lot, too. His back story, his development, extraordinary skills and down to earth character really charmed me. Woot for Halfgrip! :) <br><br><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1500130797i/23302383._SY540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Rojer <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br><br>My most awaited characters, kick-ass heroines! <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Or in this case, not much spotlight for them in this book, only some little cool scenes. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> But the thing what concerns me is the way women are portrayed. If I’m correct and the author tried to fit the cliché of the masculine power world, it’s clear why some kind a <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[sexist attitude towards women is formed from the very first pages and is hardly cast away by some tries to show courageous females. Either you’re a Mother, either a Herb Gatherer (but please be a mother, too!!!), because if not, women have two paths left: being dead or a slut. And that leads to a big WTF, I said when reading the episodes after a terrible rape one of the women experienced. I have no right to judge this character as I haven’t had such terrible experience (thanks god), but dang it, what the hell, the virgin woman was beaten and raped and after some time she starts feeling sexual attraction to her savior. Whhaaatttt? Feeling devastated emotionally and physically for a bit and voila she’s like new? WTF :O  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> <br><br>To sum up, I expected a lot more from this book as it’s a starter for the series. It is a good book with interesting worldbuilding, peculiar characters and cool action scenes with monsters. I really liked the fighting scenes and how gripping they were. But also it has some holes that need to be filled, hope the next books provide that. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1500130797i/23302384.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></span>
  <a data-text-id="4084971630194590186" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
